Multi Factor Authentication for SharePoint - Preparing for Summer Results

Dear Colleague,

In June we wrote to all customers who use SharePoint to upload assessment
material for Pearson Qualifications, advising you that we had introduced
Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA) as an additional layer of security to
help protect your centre and learner data.

While many of our centre users have successfully gone through the MFA
process for SharePoint, we are aware that you have not yet registered and
the next time you may try and log in is on a centre or learner results day.


If you are a user who may need to access your SharePoint sites over the
results or post results period, *we urge you to register for MFA now*. Our
teams will be extremely busy supporting results-related queries during
August. *If you act now, you will find it quicker to access support*,
should you need it.

Afternoon all,

I hope you're all well and enjoying the End of Year Activities!

This is a fairly long email I'm afraid, with a few key pieces of information - and lots of 'thank yous'!

It has been another fantastic year of Teacher Training at Huntington - we have increased our cohort, have offered more placements, have worked with up to 5 training providers, the list goes on! The team just keeps increasing in experience and numbers and it's great and it's what our profession needs!


  *   We say goodbye and good luck to Alex this week. Thank you Alex for all that you have done to support our trainees over your time as Maths ITT Mentor. I'm sorry that recruitment numbers haven't enabled up to host placements recently! We wish you all the best as your move on to new adventures.
  *   Huntington HR Team - thank you for supporting us with all the Safeguarding and DBS Checks so that our trainees can start their placements smoothly. I know the turn around on these can be pretty swift! So your willingness to drop everything and ensure that all checks are in place are hugely appreciated.
  *   Claire and James - thank you for setting up all matters-relating to PCs/ClassCharts/emails/printing and for your patience with some of the trainees panics with logging in! Having all of the information for log-ins etc is so important to ensure our trainees feel welcomed into school. Thank you so much.
  *   We welcome David and Natasha to the ITT mentoring Team next year! Exciting! David will be hosting a Training Teacher from Pathfinder/SHU in Social Sciences. And Natasha will be the PE Mentor (it's just so unfortunate that recruitment is down for you Natasha - hopefully this time next year will be different. Fingers Crossed).

Lastly - you, the amazing Huntington ITT Mentoring Team!

The work you do is hugely important. Without you, we would not have the next generation of teachers to care for and to educate the young people in our community.

Never before has ITT and ECT been so important in school and indeed society - with recruitment onto ITT Courses looking bleak again, it is your knowledge and coaching that is securing the future of the profession.

I repeat - The work you do is so important.

I feel proud and lucky to work alongside such great practitioners.

Have a lovely holiday when it arrives - 4 more get ups!

Alister.

Hi Paula,

Not sure if this is an internal thing or a Vital thing really - it's almost certainly not a you thing, but I'm coming to you since you sent the email about outlook calendars earlier! Hopefully you can pass this on wherever it needs to go.

I've started to get next year's lessons appearing in my calendar, like we had this year. It's been useful this year because it means I can get my day's timetable on my phone or watch, which is great.

So far only Y12 and 13 lessons seem to have gone in for next year, but there are two issues. Rather than the class code like we've had this year, it's gone in as "Y13 Language Wednesday", "Y12 Language Thursday" etc. It's much less clear, and if you have more than one class in a year group it's going to be more or less useless. Also, they've been set up with an alert to go off 15 mins before each one. It means I'm constantly fielding notifications on Outlook, on my phone and on my watch. On a 5 period day next year it's going to be unbearable!

So, before any more classes go in, please could we have them entered by class code only, as we did this year, and with no reminder/ alert?

As I say, I'm sure this isn't something you're responsible for, but I don't know who is!

Thanks, as ever,

Tom

Subject: Summer Celebration Friday 14th July


Dear All



Plans are taking shape for our Summer Celebration on Friday 14th July



  *   We hope to be on the field and the benches behind the library if the weather is kind to us.



  *   Arrival from 6.30pm. Bring your own drinks.


  *   Bistro Guy will be here with their pizza van. You can order and pay at the van, then get a buzzer to let you know when your food is ready. The full menu will be available from 6.30pm-9pm and appears below so that you can browse and plan in advance. I recommend the pineapple and nduja pizza.


  *   Entertainment will be from our very own Joao who will be playing and singing live for us 😊


  *   For those of you that are feeling sporty or competitive there will be the option to play rounders or take part in a quiz.


  *   Please take 30 seconds to let us know whether you are coming and if you plan to order food by filling in this form: https://forms.office.com/e/iMYrqgCATH . It would be helpful for Bistro Guy to know roughly how much dough to prepare and bring with them.


  *   Baz will be kicking us out and locking up at 10pm so the fun will have to stop then.


  *   If the weather's looking ropey then we'll be in the sixth form common room with the pizza van in the quad.


  *   Parking: research school, tennis courts and front of school. Cars be left overnight in the research school car park. They will be locked in overnight and available to collect on Saturday 15th from 7.30am-5pm.


  *   Toilets will be available in languages



Really looking forward to celebrating the end of term with you all!

are many different types of business models available for a business to
choose from. The razor and blade business model has been around for over a
century and is still one of the most successful types. It’s a simple
concept: sell something cheap at first but make money by selling customers
additional products and services down the road. Although the business model
is over 100 years old, it is still a profitable one.

Before using the Razor and Blade Business Model over others, let’s look at
the aspects of this model.

The Razor and Blade Business Model is a business model in which a company
sells a product or service at a low price (razor), then makes money by
selling customers replacement parts or accessories (blades) at high prices.

How a 14-Minute Video on Posture Changed My Life
<https://www.indiatelecombrief.com/wall.php?urlhash=313fa1c82eac6a61bdc7a1281%7D&lead=91556494&emailid=245674&nl=daily>

<https://www.indiatelecombrief.com/wall.php?urlhash=313fa1c82eac6a61bdc7a1281%7D&lead=91556494&emailid=245674&nl=daily>The
world is loud and full of interruptions, from the phone buzzing in your
pocket to the garbage truck backing up outside your window. It’s rare to
find yourself in an environment that is totally tranquil — rarer still to
be in a head space where you’re able to dissolve into that bubble of peace.
I crave this feeling, which I associate with sitting in a darkened eye
doctor’s office, listening to the soft click of the phoropter. I think of
doing homework alone in the dining room of a childhood piano teacher’s
house on winter evenings, waiting for my sister to finish her lesson. Or,
more recently, of the windowless phone booths in the newsroom where I used
to work, which I’d sometimes use not to conduct an interview but to sit on
the floor when I was feeling overwhelmed.

The trouble with these real-life spaces is that the bubble will inevitably
burst. The eye exam will end. It will be your turn for the piano lesson,
and it will emerge that you absolutely did not practice last week. You will
grow paranoid that your boss has clocked your absence from your desk. A
library is perhaps the ideal version of a physical space that is peaceful
in the way I’m chasing: It’s definitionally quiet, and if you don’t have
too much going on, you can stay for as long as you want, or at least until
it closes.

There is another avenue for finding environments that have a swaddling
effect on the mind, and that is the sprawling and wildly popular world of
ASMR videos on YouTube. ASMR stands for Autonomous Sensory Meridian
Response, a term coined in 2010 to describe a pleasant brain-tingling
feeling that some people experience when exposed to triggers like tapping
fingernails, crinkling fabric and whispered conversation. Many ASMR videos
involve role play, with a YouTuber taking on a specific identity to
simulate a one-on-one prom-dress fitting or lice check. While ASMR videos
can prompt that nice prickly feeling, they have the broader aim of soothing
viewers, many of whom often watch them as a stress-management tool or sleep
aid.

Hello

As you can see below a snippet from the Keeping Children Safe in Education, we require clarity and understanding on filtering and monitoring online pupil activity at Yearsley Grove Primary School.  Also, if any inappropriate sites accessed or tried to be accessed could link as an alert to CPOMs that would be ideal.

I believe that a number of schools may ask for this information as there has been an update.


The 2023 KCSIE updates also provides guidance in the form of new instructions and recommendations regarding online filtering and monitoring software to keep tabs on what sites pupils are visiting or trying to visit.

Three notable changes in the guidance state that:

·        Designated safeguarding leads (DSL) are responsible for understanding the filtering and monitoring systems each school has in place. This means that DSLs need to take the time to understand the kinds of websites students are visiting, for example.

·        “An understanding of the expectations, applicable roles and responsibilities in relation to filtering and monitoring” should be included in safeguarding and child protection training at induction for all staff.

·        Each school’s child protection policy should include how appropriate filtering and monitoring technology on school devices and school networks form part of its policies.

Safeguarding software<https://www.cpoms.co.uk/cpoms-safeguarding-software/> like CPOMS can be integrated with some of the UK’s highly trusted web filtering and monitoring service providers, such as classroom.cloud<https://classroom.cloud/>, Securus<https://www.securus-software.com/>, Senso<https://senso.cloud/gb/>, and Smoothwall<https://www.smoothwall.com/education/filter/> to ensure that if a child uses an inappropriate search term or tries to access an inappropriate website using the school’s network for example, designated safeguarding leads can be notified using the software’s automated process.


Kind regards

Joanne

Hi Adam & Marcus,

Following on from our meeting last week, I said I would send across our ‘wish list’ for September. A few things we talked about were:


  1.  Every pupil to have their own log in for the PC’s, this will be linked to their email passwords (not able to change the password) You generate the email password and we would like that to be the same for the PC as we have a record for when they forget it 😊


  1.  Dispose of Pupil DG 2, 3 4, log on and store any data on server (Temporarily) until Sam can go through and delete what is not necessary



  1.  Email distribution list – for us to be able to amend when necessary (possibly by using groups, possibly showing Sam how to do this)



  1.  Create a profile for “Complete Maths only” so pupils are not able to access anything else.



A few things since our meeting after discussion with Chris, headteacher

I know the plan was to move everything from the ‘shared drive’ over to google at some point but this never happened………..So I’m thinking that we could do this over the Summer ready for September.


  *   Move the ‘U’ drive over and give access to all staff


  *   Move the ‘V’ drive over and give access to those that are already allocated access



  *   Move the ‘S’ drive over in October. From September we will get students to safe their work in their own google drive by the End of September (this will then prevent them constantly deleting folders from the ‘S’ drive which has happened quite a lot this academic year!!



  *   Create a Visitor log in which only SLT can give to visitors when necessary



We are going to send this information out to staff on Friday this week in our bulletin.



If you think any of this is not possible in the time scales can you let me know so I can amend the information to staff or if you have any queries please don’t hesitate to contact me.

Many thanks

Lynn

Hi Emma,



I hope you are well!



We are very much looking forward to delivering the *Meet the Dell Team*
event on *Monday 10th July 2023*. I am really pleased to get in touch to
let you know that we have allocated some wonderful volunteers from Dell to
come and speak to your Year 10 students.



The session will not only include wonderful speakers from Dell
Technologies, but will also be hosted by the amazing *Louise Turner*, who
is copied into this email.



*The format of the session will run as follows: *

•              *Welcome and intro*

*•              **Intro to your Dell Team*

*•              **Q&A*

*•              **Session close  *



Your session is taking place on Microsoft Teams (meeting link available in
attached logistics pack and also here:
https://teams.microsoft.com/l/meetup-join/19%3ameeting_YmU2ZTIyMGItMjJhOS00ZDFkLTkyOWQtMjg0MzEyNTVlNDYw%40thread.v2/0?context=%7b%22Tid%22%3a%22ce8360c5-87c7-47eb-b5ef-d57be0afc988%22%2c%22Oid%22%3a%223920ca84-2402-4bc4-8d6e-c65435ac7a98%22%7d
<https://teams.microsoft.com/l/meetup-join/19%3ameeting_ZTVmNzZkZmEtZjM3Zi00MWNlLWE1NDItYmIyZDdhMGM1ZDg0%40thread.v2/0?context=%7b%22Tid%22%3a%22ce8360c5-87c7-47eb-b5ef-d57be0afc988%22%2c%22Oid%22%3a%223920ca84-2402-4bc4-8d6e-c65435ac7a98%22%7d>).
Louise and the guest speakers from Dell will join from 13:40 ready for a
prompt 13:55 start. We would encourage you to join the meeting link before
this time to iron out any tech issues, however you will be kept in the
waiting room until the start time of 13:55.



We would like to have as many students interacting with the volunteers as
possible during the session so that is *conversational* and not just a
webinar format. *Please could you ensure camera/microphones are enabled for
the session. *



*Ask students to prepare questions! *



Please ask your students to prepare a range of up to 20 questions for the
guest speakers from Dell ahead of the session.



*Please send these questions to us (**robyn.cummings@talentfoundry.org.uk*
<robyn.cummings@talentfoundry.org.uk>*), one working day before the session
via email*. We want to make sure as many questions as possible can be
covered so this will help us plan enough time for questions to be answered.




There will also be plenty of opportunity during the session to ask
questions.



*Student surveys*



You will find attached student surveys to be printed in advance of the
session and returned via post to The Talent Foundry (address included in
the attached logistics pack). If you would prefer for students to complete
the survey online, please notify us in advance and ensure that the full
cohort will be completing this (accessed here -
https://survey.zohopublic.com/zs/NlRl7X ).



Alternatively, students can also be shown a QR code on screen towards the
end of the session which will allow them to complete the survey on their
personal devices if they have one.  If you would prefer to do this, please
let us know in advance.



*Please reply to this email as soon as possible to confirm there are no
changes to the arrangements for the session*



Any further questions please don’t hesitate to get in touch. We are very
much looking forward to it!



Best wishes,

Robyn

4 to Good

for standardisation; ELT will receive invites in due course.

standardising and issuing of report cards.

Kristina

> Morning Craig,
> Transition week is coming up fast. It runs from Monday 10th July to Friday
> 14th July. You are probably aware that during that week we usually complete
> our online standardised testing with all students.
>
> There will be three tutor groups, amounting to approximately between 70
> and 90 students in the Sports Hall for periods 2, 3 and 4 each day.
>
> There are some implications for you during this week:
>
> 1. we need you to be available in the Sports Hall during periods 2, 3 and
> 4 each of the days of the testing, to trouble shoot etc
> 2. we need 90 devices (Sarah tells me we have sourced these centrally from
> the Trust - can you please make sure they are in the building before the
> end of next week so we can check they are compatible with the online
> testing website?). These devices need to be able to be plugged into the
> trolleys we have onsite at the end of each day so they start the next day
> fully charged. Obviously, on the final Friday before the week itself
> (Friday 7th July), they need to be left in the Sports Hall in their
> trolleys so they are charging over the weekend. These trolleys need to be
> left in the Sports Hall over night after each day of testing.
> 3. on each day of testing, the devices need to be open on exam desks and
> ready to go, already logged in to the school network, so that all students
> have to do is to enter their own unique code, which they will have with
> them on their exam tables.
